<h2>The Hope for Unity</h2>

<p>The division between East and West is real, and it would be dishonest to minimize it. There are genuine theological differences that cannot be dissolved by good will alone. But there is also genuine hope. The mutual excommunications of 1054 were formally lifted in 1964 by Pope Paul VI and Patriarch Athenagoras. Theological dialogues continue. Personal relationships between Catholic and Orthodox leaders have never been warmer.</p>

<p>The path to unity will be long. It may require new theological categories, new models of governance, and a willingness on both sides to distinguish between what is essential and what is merely customary. But the goal is not absorption of one tradition by the other. The goal is the restoration of the communion that once existed — a communion that honored diversity within unity, that allowed Rome and Constantinople and Alexandria and Antioch and Jerusalem to be genuinely different while remaining genuinely one.</p>

<p>That goal is worth praying for. It is worth working for. And it is worth believing in — because the Christ who prayed "that they may all be one" is not in the habit of praying for impossible things.</p>

<p>In the next step, we'll explore what East and West can learn from each other — and why the fullness of Christianity may require both lungs breathing together.</p>

